ğŸ”¹ What is a Function in C?
     ğŸ‘‰A function in C is a block of code designed to perform a specific task. It allows for code reuse, better organization, and modularity. Functions help break down complex programs into smaller, manageable chunks of code, making it easier to maintain and understand.

ğŸ”¸ 1. Function Declaration (Prototype)
    ğŸ“¥ A function declaration tells the compiler about the function's name, return type, and parameters. It gives the compiler the information it needs to call the function correctly.

ğŸ‘‰Syntax:
    return_type function_name(parameter_list);
ğŸ‘‰Example:
    int add(int, int); 






ğŸ”¸ 2. Function Definition
   ğŸ“¥  The function definition provides the actual implementation of the function. It defines the behavior and logic the function should execute.

ğŸ‘‰Syntax:
     return_type function_name(parameter_list) {
     }
ğŸ‘‰Example:
    int add(int a, int b) {
         return a + b; 
    }






ğŸ”¸ 3. Function Call
   ğŸ“¥  To execute a function, you need to call it from another part of the program, usually the main function or another function.

ğŸ‘‰Syntax:
    function_name(argument_list); 
ğŸ‘‰Example:
    int result = add(5, 3);  






ğŸ”¸ 4. Function with Parameters (Pass-by-Value)
    ğŸ“¥ In pass-by-value, the function receives copies of the arguments passed to it, meaning any changes made inside the function do not affect the original values.

Example:
#include <stdio.h>
void add(int a, int b) { 
    int sum = a + b;   
    printf("Sum: %d\n", sum); 
}
int main() {
    add(5, 10);  
    return 0;
}







ğŸ”¸ 5. Function with Return & No Parameters
    ğŸ“¥ A function can return a value and may not take any parameters.

Example:
#include <stdio.h>
int getNumber() { 
    return 10;  
}
int main() {
    int num = getNumber();  
    printf("Number: %d\n", num);  
    return 0;
}







ğŸ”¸ 6. Function with Return Value
  ğŸ“¥ A function can return a value after completing its task. The return value is typically captured in a variable in the calling function.

Example:

#include <stdio.h>
int square(int x) { 
    return x * x;  
}
int main() {
    int result = square(5);  
    printf("Square: %d\n", result);  
    return 0;
}






ğŸ”¸ 7. Function without Return Value
  ğŸ“¥ A function can also not return any value, in which case the return type is void.

Example:

#include <stdio.h>
void displayMessage() {
    printf("This function does not return a value.\n");
}
int main() {
    displayMessage(); 
    return 0;
}






ğŸ“˜8.  What is Recursion?
Recursion is a process in which a function calls itself directly or indirectly to solve a problem.

ğŸ”¶ 01. Direct Recursion
A function calls itself directly.
void fun() {
    // some code
    fun();  // Direct call to itself
}
ğŸŸ© Example:

void countdown(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    printf("%d ", n);
    countdown(n - 1);
}



ğŸ”¶ 02. Indirect Recursion
A function calls another function, and that function calls the first function again.

void A() {
    B(); // A calls B
}
void B() {
    A(); // B calls A
}
ğŸŸ© Example:

void funA(int n);
void funB(int n);

void funA(int n) {
    if (n > 0) {
        printf("%d ", n);
        funB(n - 1);
    }
}
void funB(int n) {
    if (n > 0) {
        printf("%d ", n);
        funA(n / 2);
    }
}


ğŸ”¶ 03. Tail Recursion
The recursive call is the last statement in the function.

void tail(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    printf("%d ", n);
    tail(n - 1);  // Last operation
}
ğŸŸ¢ Optimized by compiler â†’ Similar to loops.





ğŸ”¶ 04. Non-Tail Recursion
The recursive call is not the last statement; there is some operation after it.

void nonTail(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    nonTail(n - 1);  // Not the last operation
    printf("%d ", n);  // Executed after recursion
}
ğŸ›‘ Not optimized like tail recursion â†’ Uses more stack space.





ğŸ”¶ 05. Linear Recursion
Only one recursive call is made in each function activation.

void linear(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    linear(n - 1);
    printf("%d ", n);
}
âœ… Simplest form of recursion.




ğŸ”¶ 06. Tree Recursion
Function calls itself more than once in a single function activation.

void tree(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    printf("%d ", n);
    tree(n - 1);
    tree(n - 1);
}
âš ï¸ Exponential growth in function calls â†’ Used in problems like Fibonacci.
